So while the country is already making moves to develop legislation, the research will determine whether divorce is possible in the country, and what provision will replace current extended family cohabitation.

Since women in Marshall Islands are essentially “locked away” in a preservation of earlier societal mores, the idea of divorce is seen as a social taboo. While many women have been granted divorces, it’s not something that’s common–around a quarter of divorces in the country tend to be initiated by men, while the other three-quarters are initiated by women. This is largely a consequence of the fact that while women are technically free to divorce, there are many barriers and considerations that keep them from leaving unhappy marriages.
